istorical approach, Heidi Wilkins investigates a range of popular US genres including screwball comedy, the road movie and chick flicks to explore the ways that film sound can reinforce traditional assumptions about masculinity and femininity, impart ambivalent meanings to them, or even challenge and subvert the notion of gender itself. Case studies include Mildred Pierce, Aliens and The Deer Hunter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aFilm genres. 0aGender identity in motion pictures. 0aMotion picturesxSound effectsxUnited States. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxSound effects. 0aRoad filmsxHistory and criticismxUnited States. 0aRoad filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aRomance filmsxHistory and criticismxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aRomance filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen in motion pictures. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311078044440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781474406901?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474406901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474406901/original  a978-3-11-078044-4  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK